post_text:
Parents and Community,

Unfortunately the money for the grant for Day Camp has hit a dead end. Yesterday, I received the following email from HHSA, regarding the outcome of the Tulare County's CARES Act funds for our Day Camp grant:
"Looks like they were unable to fund the program. Not sure what happened. Sounds like those initial 'earmarked dollars" were reallocated to another area of need"

We are going back to the drawing board. We have a Foundation and Board meetings next week, so we will discuss options for financing and staffing. I am truly sorry for those of you still waiting for a place for your child(ren) to be supervised and academically supported while you are working. We are committed to turning over every stone looking for an avenue that would allow us to provide that support to you. We are open to ideas.

post_text:
Day Camp Update:
We partnered with HSSA-WIC and Tulare County Office of Education (TCOE), with a few other school districts, for a grant to pay for 6 day camp classes (60 kids) free of charge to parents. It went before the Tulare County Supervisor to be approved and was returned because there were more requests for this money than actual funds (Cares Act Funds). The budget needs to be reworked by HSSA. As of today, the representatives from HSSA could not tell me how this would affect our program request nor give me a time line. Sundale nor foundation have the extra staff or funds to operate a day camp. No, we can't charge for Day Camp. I am so sorry for those of you waiting. I wish I had better news. I am looking for other options just in case we don't get the grant. I will keep you all posted.
text:
Day Camp Update:
We partnered with HSSA-WIC and Tulare County Office of Education (TCOE), with a few other school districts, for a grant to pay for 6 day camp classes (60 kids) free of charge to parents. It went before the Tulare County Supervisor to be approved and was returned because there were more requests for this money than actual funds (Cares Act Funds). The budget needs to be reworked by HSSA. As of today, the representatives from HSSA could not tell me how this would affect our program request nor give me a time line. Sundale nor foundation have the extra staff or funds to operate a day camp. No, we can't charge for Day Camp. I am so sorry for those of you waiting. I wish I had better news. I am looking for other options just in case we don't get the grant. I will keep you all posted.

Sundale Foundation for Students and Community, Inc.
July 30 at 1:10 PM ·

Sundale Foundation Hours of Operation are 7:30 AM-4:30 PM.

The preschool’s first day of school is August 3rd, 2020. Day Care for school age children will begin August 10th, 2020

Day Care will also be available for school age students. There are limited spots available and it will be based on levels of priority. (staff, First responders, essential workers, etc.). The price is $30 a day and the program is 5 days a week. We will follow the same calendar as Sundale School. To place your child on the list for day care please email office@sundalefoundation.com. In your email please provide the child's first and last name, parents name, child’s DOB, grade they will be in, the best contact number, email, and please specify if both parents are working, first responders, etc.

** This is subject to change if regulations change due to Covid-19

post_text:
Tulare County is on the Covid-19 monitoring list, therefore we will have to start school with distance learning. In order to physically open and bring students back on campus, our County will have to be off the monitoring list for 14 consecutive days.

We will keep our plans for A/B days, coming back 5 days so we are ready to bring students back when Tulare County is off of monitoring list for 14 consecutive days.

More information coming regarding how to get devices in hotspots, the expectations for distance learning, any text books or materials that may be needed. This information will be shared in a variety of ways (Facebook, Facebook group, the Remind App, Website, the All Call system, mail and emails). If you have questions, please email terri.rufert@sundale.org, cindy.gist@sundale.org, or call 569-688-7451.

post_text:
When will Sundale decide which plan to reopen with?
The Sundale School Board will make that decision at the Board meeting on July 28th, 2020 in room 22 at 7:30. If we end up with too many people, we will put a note on the door that it was moved to the multi-purpose building.

Can parents attend?
Absolutely. Board meetings are always open to the public.

Can a parent share their thoughts with the board?
Always. Here are the rules:
1. You have 3 minutes to talk about any item on the agenda and the board will listen but not respond back.
2. If you want to discuss an item that may not be on the agenda, you need to submit a letter or email to Mrs. Rufert for approval by the Wednesday at preceding the board meeting which is almost every 2nd and 4th Tuesday.

post_text: Sundale is considering 3 different plans to start next year with safety precautions for each schedule- 1) bring all the kids back 5 days per week, 2) blended learning on A/B days (2 days per weeks on campus) with an additional day for intervention and enrichment or 3) full distance learning. The School Board will make the final decision at the July 28th board meeting. In the meantime, we will be preparing our staff, students and parents/guardians for all three plans so we will be ready to start on August 5th. Please join the Sundale Group for parents/guardians and alumni for more information and to share your thoughts, questions and concerns.

In addition, during this process of getting it on Youtube, additional edits are now needed. Somehow our original edits did not stick. This evening, we are hoping to be able to announce the day and time it will be ready. We are shooting and HOPING for Sunday at 6 or 6:30. We will send out a note on our social media and remind. The ALL call will have to wait until tomorrow. Stay tuned and cross your fingers.

As soon as it can be correctly uploaded, I will let you know. Hopefully sometime between Friday and Sunday.

I am so sorry for the delay. It is really out of our control at this time. Thank you for your understanding and patience.

Each graduate will receive a free DVD of the graduation. The front and back cover of the DVD was designed by our very own Sundale 2020 Graduates, Caitlyn Dizon.

It was really great to see you at the Sundale Graduation Walk. Congratulations, graduates!

8th Grade Graduation Checklist . 2020 . Sundale School .

Proudly post your yard sign for all neighbors to see!

Hang up your gown, only iron on a low setting, steaming it is best! (you can put it in the bathroom when you take a shower too!)

Submit all pictures for virtual graduation to Mrs. Dukes (rae.dukes@sundale.org)
One 8th grade pic (you should look nice in this one)
One baby picture
Three middle school pictures that represent you (no selfies)

Show up on your day and time to Ag. Science Area at Sundale:
Bring your gown (shouldn’t be wrinkled!)
Dress nicely (like you're going to church...or taking graduation photos!)
Bring any medals or pins you have received throughout middle school
Smile!
If you are not coming on your scheduled day and time, email Mrs. Beck for directions on what to do instead. (shannon.beck@sundale.org)

Continue to complete and submit all work, join Zooms, Flipgrids (for Beck) and keep in contact with your teachers. (Beck, Dukes, Tiner & Pursell)

Go to Sundale School YouTube channel graduation night and watch the virtual ceremony! (June 3, 2020 @ 6:00 pm)

California State Parks PORTS Distance Learning Program added a new photo to the album: PORTS Home Learning Programs.
April 9 at 7:23 PM ·

Hey Parents and Teachers!

We are excited to announce next week's line up of Home Learning Programs! Which @CalforniaStateParks will you explore with us? Sign up for one, or sign up for all!

Pre-registration is required for all programs. Register in advance for each program by visiting the calendar of events on our website: www.ports-ca.us

Teachers! We have dedicated a new page on our website just for you! Please check it out to learn all of the ways that you can connect your students to both our Home Learning Programs and our "traditional" PORTS Programs.
https://www.ports-ca.us/teachers

A HUGE thank you to all of our #PORTSFan's out there! The incredible comments, posts we've been tagged in, and photos that you have shared, have been the bright spot of our week! And thanks to all of you, we have almost reached 20,000 students since starting Home Learning Programs on March 17th! We could never have done this without you!

post_text:
Chromebooks and/or headphones will be available for checkout to current Sundale students on Tuesday, March 31 at 11:00-12:00 and 5:30-6:30 in front of the multipurpose room.

The Technology Loan Agreement is available on our website. Please print the form, complete, and bring it with you Tuesday to expedite the checkout process. Each student checking out a Chromebook needs their own completed form. If the parent is not able to be present to pick up the Chromebook, we ask that they sign the agreement ahead of time and the adult picking up will also need to sign the agreement. The parent or current Sundale student must be present for pick up.

We are requiring that families have internet access prior to checking out a Chromebook. At this time, we are not offering hotspots. See our website for information on free and low cost internet services.

https://www.sundaleschool.com/students/covid-19-resources

Please email katie.biangone@sundale.org with questions.

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:

Due to the ongoing COVID-19 Pandemic, Sundale UESD will remain closed until further notice. The following criteria will be used to determine when and if Sundale UESD is to reopen for student attendance:

1. The California State Shelter in Place order has been lifted.
2. The number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Tulare County has remained constant for a two week period or declined.
3. The directive to Social Distance has been removed by the state of California.
4. The limit placed on social gatherings has been removed by the state of California.

I have truly enjoyed seeing so many of your children through the zoom meetings and Flipgrid app. It is important for your child(ren) to do their work so they are prepared for when they return and going to the next grade. Please make sure to stay connected to your teachers so you can make sure your students don't fall behind. I will be updating you on how to turn in the vwork your student had been given over these last 3 weeks, so stay tuned.

On another note, I have also enjoyed seeing how many families are taking advantages of this time together by working together and having fun. As much work that this closure had required of all of us, Keep your faith and family at the forefront. You can make some wonderful family memories during this time. Laughter is an amazing cure for stress, anxiety and depression. Good can come from turmoil.

Here is a picture of my in depth sticker art with granddaughter. Priceless.

Have a fabulous day.

Tulare County Office of Education
March 20 at 3:44 PM ·

In an effort to assist parents and teachers seeking alternative ways to educate children at home due to school closures, TCOE has created a website of free distance learning resources! There are many grade level-specific categories in a variety of content levels to choose from. Also included are resources for student social/emotional learning – all in an easy-to-navigate format. Parents and educators are encouraged to visit the site frequently as new resources will be added on an ongoing basis. Please share the link with others who may benefit from these resources. Visit tcoe.org/DistanceLearning to learn more.

post_text:
March 19, 2020 UPDATE

Here is the latest update on the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. As you may have heard, Governor Newsom announced just moments ago a Statewide Stay at Home Order. We do not have the text of the Order yet but we understand that it takes effect this evening.

Absent information to the contrary, we will continue to provide educational and meal services to our children. Schools have generally been exempted from these orders as “essential governmental services.” Moreover, through the remote learning program that we have implemented, we believe that these services can continue to be provided while protecting the health, safety and welfare of our staff.

I will keep you updated as I learn more.

Again, please stay safe and healthy!

As of tomorrow, Mon. March 16, Sundale will be closed through April 13 for precautionary measures due to the Coronavirus. As of right now, school will resume on April 14. We will be mailing home packets of school work to be completed during this closing, as well as report cards. If you have any questions about the work, you can contact your teachers via email. I encourage you to keep up on your social media for updates. The office will be open to take phone calls. Please do not come on campus unless you need to pick up your child’s textbooks in order to complete the packets.
Thank you!

post_text: Today our top 20 Sundale Shake students presented at J.D. Heiskell’s in Tulare. Five teams addressed issues that face our community, with each putting their own spin on possible solutions that could benefit our downtown area and city as a whole. Congratulations to our winning team, the Olive Branch. Another big congratulations to our top 3 finalists that will move on to our final round, with one being crowned as the Sundale Shake Champion. A big thank you to JDHCO, CleVR Escape, as well as our amazing coaches and judges!
